{"tool":"write_file","args":{"path":"docs/SUBSYSTEMS.md","content":"# SUBSYSTEMS: USB-C Power Breakout\n\nStage 2 — architecture. This document decomposes the SPEC (`docs/SPEC.md`)\ninto block-level subsystems, one section each, with reasoning and key\nvalues. Every numeric budget in SPEC.md §3 is carried into the subsystem it\ngoverns. No parts are selected here (that is the part-selection stage); this\nis the block diagram and the constraints each block must meet.\n\n## 1. Block diagram (in prose)\n\n```\n   USB-C source (charger/host)\n           |\n     [USB-C receptacle]  <-- VBUS, GND, CC1, CC2 (D+/D- unused)\n        |        |\n        |        +--> [CC sink termination: Rd on CC1, Rd on CC2 -> GND]\n        |\n      VBUS_IN\n        |\n     [ESD/surge: TVS VBUS->GND at the connector]\n        |\n     [Short-circuit protection device]  (VBUS_IN -> VBUS_OUT)\n        |\n      VBUS_OUT ------+-----------------+-------------------+\n        |            |                 |                   |\n   [Power-good     [Screw terminal   [2x2 0.1\"          (GND plane\n    LED + Rs        VBUS/GND]         header VBUS/GND]    common to all)\n    -> GND]\n```\n\nSignal flow is one-directional: 5V enters at the USB-C receptacle, passes\nthrough ESD clamping and the short-circuit protection device, and is\ndistributed to the two output connectors and the indicator LED. CC1/CC2\nbranch off at the connector purely to present the sink pull-downs; they\ncarry no power and no data. D+/D- are intentionally unconnected (SPEC §6).\n\nThere is **no MCU subsystem and no connectivity subsystem** — see §8.\n\n## 2. Input / USB-C receptacle subsystem\n\n**Role:** Accept 5V VBUS + GND from a USB-C cable, sink-side only. Expose\nCC1/CC2 to the CC termination block. D+/D- not routed (SPEC §6).\n\n**Governing budgets:**\n- Input voltage: 5V nominal, must survive up to 6V (SPEC §3). All parts on\n  the VBUS_IN node inherit the 6V survive rating as their minimum working\n  voltage; part selection should pick ≥10V-rated caps/TVS for margin.\n- Output current rating: 3A continuous (SPEC §3/§3.1). The receptacle's\n  VBUS and GND power contacts must be rated ≥3A. This drives receptacle\n  choice toward a part whose VBUS/GND pins (often doubled) carry 3A.\n- Board area ≤30x20mm (SPEC §3): the receptacle dominates one edge; its\n  footprint is the largest single mechanical consumer and constrains layout.\n\n**Key architectural values:**\n- Wired as a **sink** (UFP power role). Only VBUS, GND, CC1, CC2 used.\n- CC1 and CC2 are brought out **separately**, each to its own Rd (see §3) —\n  not tied together — so the board works in either plug orientation.\n\n## 3. CC sink termination subsystem\n\n**Role:** Make the board look like a legal USB-C 5V sink so a compliant\nsource turns VBUS on. Each CC pin terminates through a pull-down (Rd) to GND\n(SPEC §2.3). No CC logic, no PD PHY, no e-marker.\n\n**Governing budgets / rules:**\n- Two separate Rd resistors, one on CC1 and one on CC2, each to GND. Using\n  one shared resistor is wrong — it would misrepresent the termination when\n  both CC lines are used and breaks orientation independence.\n- The **Rd value** (nominally 5.1kΩ per the Type-C spec) and its full\n  rationale are deferred to `docs/DECISIONS.md` at part selection, per SPEC\n  §2.3 which flags this as the single detail most likely to be wrong. This\n  document only fixes the topology: two pull-downs, CC1->GND and CC2->GND.\n- Quiescent impact: with VBUS present the source's Rp + this Rd form a\n  divider; the standing current through each Rd is sub-100µA at 5V and is\n  part of the <2mA quiescent budget (SPEC §3.2, \"everything else\" ≤1mA\n  slice). Comfortable margin.\n\n## 4. Short-circuit protection subsystem\n\n**Role:** Protect the output, connector, and upstream source against a\ndownstream short without destroying the board (SPEC §2.5).\n\n**Governing budgets:**\n- Must pass 3A continuous without tripping (SPEC §3 output rating). Trip\n  threshold assumed 3.5–4A (SPEC §5, ASSUMED) — headroom above 3A so normal\n  full-load use never nuisance-trips.\n- Method assumed: **resettable / auto-recovering current limiter**\n  (eFuse or PTC-style), not a one-time fuse (SPEC §5). A breadboard tool\n  should recover after a transient short.\n- Voltage: sits on the VBUS path, so rated for ≥6V survive (SPEC §3).\n- **Quiescent draw is a hard constraint:** if an active device (eFuse) is\n  chosen, its own supply/bias current counts against the ≤1mA \"everything\n  else\" slice of the 2mA budget (SPEC §3.2). A PTC's leakage is negligible\n  but its series resistance and I²t must still pass 3A. The specific device,\n  its trip point, and its Iq are recorded in DECISIONS.md at part selection\n  and must be checked against SPEC §3.2 there.\n- Cost: contributes to the <$3 qty-100 BOM (SPEC §3). eFuse vs PTC is partly\n  a cost/quiescent tradeoff resolved at part selection.\n\n## 5. ESD / surge protection subsystem\n\n**Role:** Clamp ESD/surge events entering at the user-facing USB-C\nconnector (SPEC §5, ASSUMED). One low-capacitance TVS across VBUS/GND at the\nreceptacle.\n\n**Governing budgets:**\n- Working voltage above 6V survive level, clamp below the ratings of\n  downstream parts (SPEC §3).\n- Placed at the connector, before the protection device, so surge energy is\n  shunted at the entry point.\n- Cost/area: a single small TVS; must fit the <$3 BOM (SPEC §3) — flagged in\n  SPEC §5 for revisit if it conflicts with the cost target.\n- No data lines to protect (D+/D- unused), so this is VBUS-only; no data-line\n  ESD array is needed.\n\n## 6. Output distribution subsystem\n\n**Role:** Deliver VBUS_OUT/GND to the two user connectors (SPEC §2.2):\na 2-pin 3.5mm screw terminal and a 2x2 0.1\" pin header.\n\n**Governing budgets:**\n- Both connectors and all copper between the protection device and them must\n  carry **3A continuous** (SPEC §3/§3.1). Screw terminal: pick a 3.5mm part\n  rated ≥3A. Header: 0.1\" pins are typically rated a few amps each; VBUS and\n  GND each get one pin of the 2x2 (the 2x2 = VBUS, VBUS? no) — topology is\n  one VBUS pin pair and one GND pin pair, or VBUS/GND on each row; exact pin\n  assignment fixed at schematic stage. The point here: the header must be\n  wired so the 3A path has adequate pin/copper.\n- \"3A\" is a **rating, not a negotiated guarantee** (SPEC §3.1) — silkscreen\n  and any labels on these connectors must not imply PD or guaranteed 3A.\n- Trace width / copper weight to hit 3A on 2-layer 1oz (SPEC §4) is a layout\n  obligation, deferred to the layout stage.\n\n## 7. UI / power-good LED subsystem\n\n**Role:** A single visible LED that is on whenever VBUS is present (SPEC\n§2.4). LED + series resistor from VBUS_OUT to GND.\n\n**Governing budgets:**\n- **LED branch current ≤1mA** (SPEC §3.2, ASSUMED split of the 2mA total).\n  At ~5V this sets the series resistor: a modern high-efficiency LED is\n  clearly visible at well under 1mA, so the series resistor is sized for\n  a few hundred µA to stay safely inside the slice. Exact LED + resistor at\n  part selection; the ≤1mA ceiling is the hard architectural value.\n- Combined with the \"everything else\" ≤1mA slice, total quiescent stays\n  under the 2mA hard budget (SPEC §3).\n- Passive size ≥0603 (SPEC §4) for the resistor and LED.\n- Indicates VBUS presence only — not \"5V regulated\" or \"PD active\"; there is\n  no regulation or negotiation on this board.\n\n## 8. Absent subsystems (intentional — not an oversight)\n\nThese blocks appear in the stage-2 template but **do not exist on this\nboard**, by design and per SPEC:\n\n- **MCU / compute:** none. The board performs no logic, no CC reading, no\n  current-limit enforcement (SPEC §1, §3.1). Adding an MCU would blow the\n  <$3 BOM and the <2mA quiescent budget and is explicitly out of the brief.\n- **Connectivity / data:** none. D+/D- are not routed to anything (SPEC §6).\n  No USB data, no wireless, no PD communication PHY.\n- **Power conversion / regulation:** none. Output is pass-through 5V VBUS;\n  there is no buck/boost/LDO. \"5V nominal\" is whatever the source supplies\n  (SPEC §3.1). No inductor, no switching node.\n- **Negotiation (USB-PD/BC1.2):** none (SPEC §1, §6). Sink presents Rd only.\n\nRecording their absence here prevents a later reviewer from reading a\nmissing MCU/regulator/PD chip as a mistake.\n\n## 9. Budget traceability summary\n\n| SPEC §3 budget | Owning subsystem(s) | How held |\n|---|---|---|\n| 3A continuous rating | Input (§2), Protection (§4), Output (§6) | Connector/device ratings ≥3A; trace width at layout |\n| 5V nominal / 6V survive | Input (§2), ESD (§5), Protection (§4) | All VBUS-node parts rated ≥6V (≥10V chosen for margin) |\n| <2mA quiescent (incl. LED) | LED (§7) ≤1mA + Protection/CC (§3,§4) ≤1mA | Split per SPEC §3.2; verified at part selection |\n| Board area ≤30x20mm | Input (§2) + Output (§6) footprints | Layout stage |\n| BOM <$3 @ qty100 | all | Part selection stage |\n| Mounting: 2x M3, 24mm pitch | Mechanical | Layout stage |\n\n## 10. Traceability\n\nSource: `docs/SPEC.md` (all §3 budgets, §5 assumptions) and `brief.md`.\nItems marked ASSUMED there (protection method/trip, TVS, quiescent split,\ntemperature) remain assumptions here and are resolved at part selection.\n"}}
